Sentence.Text: Wednesday 08:00 GMT .
Markets are giving off mixed signals as investors continue to mither about the global economic impact of fiscal stresses in Europe and the US .

Moves in some major barometers point to a mild risk appetite , with the dollar index dipping 0.1 per cent , US benchmark Treasury yields adding 3 basis points to 1.63 per cent and copper up 0.2 per cent to $ 3.48 a pound .
But the picture in stocks is more confused as the FTSE All-World index is barely changed and sat near two-month lows .
Asian bourses were generally positive , though somewhat reticent as they awaited the conclusion of China s party Congress to chose new leaders .
Investors will try to infer from the outcome an indication of future policy direction in the world s second-largest economy .
The FTSE Asia Pacific index is up 0.1 per cent , after the Shanghai Composite rose 0.4 per cent and Tokyo s Nikkei 225 managed to break a seven day losing streak with a gain of just 0.04 per cent .
Japanese exporters may benefit on Thursday from a sharp drop in the yen , which came after the market closed when prime minister Yoshihiko Noda said he may call elections next month .
The FTSE Eurofirst 300 has opened with a loss of 0.3 per cent , mainly reflecting Wall Street s inability to hold a rally in the previous session .
But according to US stock futures , the S & amp ; P 500 in New York will add 0.5 per cent later in the day , helped by some well-received results from Cisco .
This would still leave the US benchmark index just below the 200-day moving average of 1,382 , rendering it vulnerable to further declines , according to many technical analysts .

US equities have fallen to three-month lows declining in conjunction with other so-called `` risk assets '' as a disappointing corporate earnings season was followed by renewed fretting over a potential default by Greece , prevarication by Spain over asking for aid , and more lately , a focus on the potential economic damage caused by the US falling off its `` fiscal cliff '' .
Analysts at Barclays highlighted in a note the difficulties facing traders as they try to assess the impact competing factors will have on markets over coming months .
`` The outlook for risky assets toward year-end is challenging , to say the least .
On the one hand , the potential for negative shocks from of the US fiscal cliff and persistent problems in Greece and Spain pose downside risks to markets .
`` On the other , markets are flush with liquidity and the Fed put remains in place , which many see as limiting the extent of any further downdraft '' .
The `` Fed put '' refers to the US central bank s propensity to intervene to support asset markets , such as its $ 40bn a month of mortgage-backed securities purchases under the ongoing QE3 program .
More clues on the Fed s thinking will be provided later on Wednesday , when the minutes of its October policy meeting are published .
Before that the latest snapshot of the US economy will be released when October retail sales numbers are published at 1330 GMT .
Investors will be keen to see how confident the US consumer is as the crucial festive shopping season approaches .
Australian households are certainly feeling a bit more chipper .
The Aussie dollar is up 0.1 per cent to $ 1.0445 and Sydney s S & amp ; P\/ASX 200 stock index added 0.2 per cent , after a survey showed consumer sentiment rose to a 19 month high .
Meanwhile , the euro is up 0.2 per cent to $ 1.2724 , but still flirting with two-month lows as worries about when Greece will receive its next trance of aid continue to weigh on the currency .

Indeed , underlying eurozone debt tensions ensure Spanish 10-year bond yields remain elevated at 5.84 per cent though they did retreat from the 6 per cent mark rather swiftly on Tuesday as the European Central Bank is seen in the background ready to suppress yields if requested .
All this stress is probably helping to attract funds into gold .
The bullion is up $ 2 to $ 1,727 an ounce just $ 4 or so below a four-week closing high .
Additional reporting by Song Jung-a in Seoul and Vivianne Rodrigues in New York
